teach Cerwonka, then new to the discipline, the basic tools and subtle intuition needed for anthropological fieldwork. The result is a strikingly original dissection of the processual ethics and politics of method in ethnography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  atheory, theoretical, academic, scholarly, ethnography, ethnographic, fieldwork, methods, process, construction, teaching, educational, higher ed, college, university, grad school, textbook, professor, teacher, improvisation, research, analysis, explanation, unpredictable, correspondence, political science, australia, anthropology, anthropological, ethics, politics.1 aCerwonka, Allaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalkki, Liisa H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMalkki, Liisa H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalkki, Liisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226100289423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226100289/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles